## Business Logic

### 1. Summary of the Account Service

The Account Service is designed to manage user accounts, providing functionalities for account creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion. It integrates with external services to validate account statuses and uses messaging systems to handle asynchronous communication. The service employs a relational database for persistent storage of account information, while also utilizing a non-relational database for managing bank-related data. The service is built using a microservices architecture, ensuring scalability and maintainability. It exposes a RESTful API for interaction with clients, enabling operations such as listing all accounts, fetching account details by ID, and managing account lifecycle events.

### 2. Service Overview Table

| **Base Path**               | **Source Repository**                     | **Description**                                                                                     |
|-----------------------------|-------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`                 | [GitHub Repo Link](#)                    | API for managing user accounts, including creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion functionalities. |

### 3. Overall API Specification

| **Endpoint**          | **Method** | **Description**                                   | **Request Body**         | **Responses**                                                                                                          |
|----------------------|------------|---------------------------------------------------|--------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`          | GET        | Retrieve all accounts                            | -                        | 200 OK: List of accounts in JSON format.                                                                             |
| `/accounts`          | POST       | Create a new account                            | Account object in JSON   | 201 Created: Account created successfully, returns the created account object.<br>400 Bad Request: If account ID already exists. |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | GET        | Retrieve account by ID                          | -                        | 200 OK: Account details in JSON format.<br>404 Not Found: If account with the specified ID does not exist.           |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | PUT        | Update an existing account                      | Account object in JSON   | 200 OK: Account updated successfully, returns the updated account object.<br>404 Not Found: If account with the specified ID does not exist. |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | DELETE     | Delete an account by ID                         | -                        | 204 No Content: Account deleted successfully.<br>404 Not Found: If account with the specified ID does not exist.     |

### 4. Endpoints Summary

- **GET `/accounts`**: Fetch all accounts.
- **POST `/accounts`**: Create a new account.
- **GET `/accounts/{id}`**: Retrieve an account by its ID.
- **PUT `/accounts/{id}`**: Update an existing account.
- **DELETE `/accounts/{id}`**: Delete an account by its ID. 

This structured format provides a comprehensive overview of the Account Service, detailing its purpose, functionality, and API specifications.

## Plant UML script

Here is a PlantUML sequence diagram script based on the provided business logic. This script includes all key actors/participants, main interactions, critical decision points, and follows the PlantUML sequence diagram syntax.

```plantuml
@startuml
actor User as "Users/Clients"
participant "Account Service" as AccountService
participant "Bank Service" as BankService
participant "External Validation Service" as ValidationService
participant "RabbitMQ" as RabbitMQ
participant "Kafka" as Kafka

== Account Creation ==
User -> AccountService: POST /accounts\n{Account Object}
AccountService -> AccountService: Validate Account ID
alt Account ID exists
    AccountService -> User: 400 Bad Request\n"Account ID already exists"
else
    AccountService -> BankService: Validate Bank Code
    alt Valid Bank Code
        AccountService -> AccountService: Create Account
        AccountService -> RabbitMQ: Publish Account Created Event
        AccountService -> User: 201 Created\n{Created Account}
    else
        AccountService -> User: 400 Bad Request\n"Invalid Bank Code"
    end
end

== Account Retrieval ==
User -> AccountService: GET /accounts/{id}
AccountService -> AccountService: Check Account Existence
alt Account exists
    AccountService -> AccountService: Fetch Account Details
    AccountService -> ValidationService: Validate Account Status
    ValidationService -> AccountService: Return Account Status
    AccountService -> User: 200 OK\n{Account Object}
else
    AccountService -> User: 404 Not Found\n"Account does not exist"
end

== Account Update ==
User -> AccountService: PUT /accounts/{id}\n{Account Object}
AccountService -> AccountService: Check Account Existence
alt Account exists
    AccountService -> AccountService: Update Account Details
    AccountService -> Kafka: Publish Account Updated Event
    AccountService -> User: 200 OK\n{Updated Account}
else
    AccountService -> User: 404 Not Found\n"Account does not exist"
end

== Account Deletion ==
User -> AccountService: DELETE /accounts/{id}
AccountService -> AccountService: Check Account Existence
alt Account exists
    AccountService -> AccountService: Delete Account
    AccountService -> User: 204 No Content
else
    AccountService -> User: 404 Not Found\n"Account does not exist"
end

== Account Management ==
User -> AccountService: GET /accounts
AccountService -> AccountService: Retrieve All Accounts
AccountService -> User: 200 OK\n[List of Accounts]

@enduml
```

### Explanation of the Diagram:
1. **Actors**:
   - Users/Clients interact with the Account Service.
   - The Account Service communicates with the Bank Service, External Validation Service, RabbitMQ, and Kafka.

2. **Main Interactions**:
   - Account creation, retrieval, update, and deletion processes are depicted with clear messages.
   - Each action checks for critical conditions, such as account existence and bank code validity.

3. **Decision Points**:
   - The diagram includes decision points for validating account IDs, checking the existence of accounts, and validating bank codes.

4. **Message Clarity**:
   - Each interaction includes descriptive messages that indicate the request and response status.

5. **Components**:
   - All components involved in the service (Account Service, Bank Service, RabbitMQ, Kafka, and Validation Service) are represented.

This sequence diagram provides a comprehensive view of the Account Management process as described in the business logic.

### 1. Retrieve All Accounts

#### API Specification
- **Endpoint URL**: `/accounts`
- **HTTP Method**: `GET`
- **Authentication & Authorization Requirements**: None
- **Description of the API Functionality**: Retrieves a list of all user accounts.

#### Request Parameters
| Parameter | Type   | Required | Constraints | Description                   |
|-----------|--------|----------|-------------|-------------------------------|
| None      | -      | No       | -           | No request parameters needed.  |

#### Sample Request
```http
GET /accounts HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
```

#### Response Parameters
| Field          | Type         | Description                           |
|----------------|--------------|---------------------------------------|
| accounts       | Array of    | List of account objects               |
|                | Account     |                                       |

#### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dob": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "XYZ123"
    }
  ]
}
```

#### Components Involved
- Account Service
- Database

#### Data Mapping
| Source Entity    | Target Entity | Relationship                     | Transformation             |
|------------------|---------------|----------------------------------|-----------------------------|
| AccountEntity    | Account       | One-to-Many                      | AccountManagerMapper        |

#### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "500",
    "message": "Internal Server Error"
  }
}
```

#### Root Exception Details
| Name               | Description                     | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory | Notes                     |
|--------------------|---------------------------------|----------------|--------|-----------|---------------------------|
| InternalError      | An unexpected error occurred    | Payload        | JSON   | Yes       | General server error      |

#### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message              | Description                    |
|-----------|----------------------|--------------------------------|
| 500       | Internal Server Error | An unexpected error occurred   |

### 2. Create a New Account

#### API Specification
- **Endpoint URL**: `/accounts`
- **HTTP Method**: `POST`
- **Authentication & Authorization Requirements**: None
- **Description of the API Functionality**: Creates a new user account.

#### Request Parameters
| Parameter | Type         | Required | Constraints            | Description                    |
|-----------|--------------|----------|------------------------|--------------------------------|
| account   | Account     | Yes      | Must include all fields | Account object to be created   |

#### Sample Request
```http
POST /accounts HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1990-01-01",
  "bankCode": "XYZ123"
}
```

#### Response Parameters
| Field          | Type         | Description                           |
|----------------|--------------|---------------------------------------|
| account        | Account     | The created account object            |

#### Sample Response
```json
{
  "account": {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "John Doe",
    "email": "john.doe@example.com",
    "accountNumber": "123456789",
    "accountType": "savings",
    "dob": "1990-01-01",
    "bankCode": "XYZ123"
  }
}
```

#### Components Involved
- Account Service
- Database
- RabbitMQ (for event publishing)

#### Data Mapping
| Source Entity    | Target Entity | Relationship                     | Transformation             |
|------------------|---------------|----------------------------------|-----------------------------|
| Account          | AccountEntity | One-to-One                      | AccountManagerMapper        |

#### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "400",
    "message": "Account ID already exists"
  }
}
```

#### Root Exception Details
| Name               | Description                           | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory | Notes                     |
|--------------------|---------------------------------------|----------------|--------|-----------|---------------------------|
| BadRequest          | Invalid input data                    | Payload        | JSON   | Yes       | Account ID duplication    |

#### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                         | Description                             |
|-----------|---------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|
| 400       | Bad Request                    | Account ID already exists               |
| 500       | Internal Server Error          | An unexpected error occurred            |
